result.execSummary:
The defendant Tiffany L Jewell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Tiffany L Jewell in court with attorney Victoria Mccandless.  Peter A. Hahn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

 Off the record discussion.  PSI report received by parties. PSI reviewed by parties. Correction made to labeled page 2. 
 
AS TO COUNT 1:
Court ordered defendant to serve 12 MONTHS in the House of Correction concurrent with count 2 and 3 of 15CF2049 and consecutive to any other sentence; release for work, inmate work assignments within the House of Correction, The Day Reporting Center (if eligible); with credit for 3 days time served. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring.

AS TO COUNT 2:
Court ordered defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction concurrent with count 1 and 3 of 15CF2049 and consecutive to any other sentence; release for work, inmate work assignments within the House of Correction, The Day Reporting Center (if eligible); with credit for 3 days time served. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring. 

AS TO COUNT 3:
Court ordered defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction concurrent with count 1 and 2 of 15CF2049 and consecutive to any other sentence; release for work, inmate work assignments within the House of Correction, The Day Reporting Center (if eligible); with credit for 3 days time served. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring. 

COURT STAYED THE SENTENCES and placed defendant on probation for 2 YEARS. Court will allow for early release for probation if defendant successfully completes 18 months of probation without any violations. 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION AS TO COUNT 1:
  - Court ordered defendant to serve 6 MONTHS CONDITION TIME  in the House of Correction without goodtime credit; release for The Day Reporting Center, work, inmate work assignments at the House of correction. Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring. Imposed and stayed to use at the request of DOC agent. 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety: No use or possession/use of alcohol or controlled substances without a valid prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment and successfully complete recommended treatment.  
- Department of Corrections must conduct drug and alcohol testing.
- Defendant to notify Department of Corrections agent of all prescriptions within 3 business days/72 hours of receiving prescription from medical professional.
- Fill all prescriptions at one pharmacy, unless otherwise approved by Department of Corrections Agent, and notify the Department of Corrections agent of the pharmacy used. 
- No possession of any drug paraphernalia for personal use, manufacturing, delivering or for distribution.
- No possession of any firearms or weapons, firearm ammunition, firearm magazine, firearm holster, any body armor, taser or dangerous weapon.
- Maintain full time employment/school or a combination of both. 
- No contact with LaTonya M.
- Mental Health Evaluation and any recommended treatment. 
- Court recommends Trauma Informed Mental Health Treatment. 
- Defendant to follow all conditions of probation set in 14CM2483 Milwaukee County Case. 
- Fine is set at ZERO.
- As to count 1 Drivers license suspension is not imposed.
- Provide DNA sample, if not already done. 
- Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge, during the course of probation to the probation agent. Any remaining balance due at the end of probation and will become immediately due or civil judgment to be entered. Defendant may satisify cost, fees, and assessments through 60 hours of community service (20 hours for each count), to be completed by the end of probation. 

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.

The Court informed the defendant of requirements and penalties applicable under s. 941.29(1m) or (4m).

AS TO COUNT 1, 2, and 3: 

The defendant was advised of her Constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Jury Instructions and Addendum to Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting. Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible. 

Parties advised the Court will listen to statements by counsel, any victims, and the defendant. Any other statements must be in writing and provided to the Court 3 business days in advance of the sentencing. 

Defense requested presentence investigation report. Court ordered a presentence investigation without a recommendation.  Order for presentence investigation signed and filed.
